function getCultureKeyInsight(obs,metrics,sim){
  const interior=metrics.filter(m=>m.isInterior).map(m=>m.name);
  const top=metrics[0]?.name;

  if(obs==='Earth') return `From Earth, the interior/exterior split produces two classes of deity: the bound heralds (Mercury, Venus) who are forever associated with thresholds, impermanence, and the liminal hour — and the free wanderers (Mars, Jupiter, Saturn) who rule the night sky and carry authority. This structural contrast is what generated the classical planetary hierarchy. Change the vantage point, and the contract between gods reshuffles entirely.`;

  if(interior.includes('Earth')) return `<strong>Earth is a Morning Star from ${obs}.</strong> This is the deepest cultural consequence. Any civilization on ${obs} would mythologize Earth the way Earth cultures mythologized Venus: as a near-Sun jewel, brilliant at dawn and dusk, colored unmistakably blue-white, associated with water, origin, promise, and things that cannot be reached. Earth would be the "homeland star" — the deity of longing, of the home you cannot return to, of memory preserved across vast distances. No ${obs} civilization that watches the sky would fail to notice the blue point of light near the Sun, blazing brightest at its elongation, and wonder what world it might be.`;

  if(sim<0.1) return `<strong>The inner solar system is invisible.</strong> From ${obs}, Mercury, Venus, Earth, and Mars are all interior — lost in the solar glare for much of the year, appearing only briefly at dawn or dusk, never reaching midnight. The civilizational consequence is immense: the traditional cast of classical planetary mythology (Mercury the messenger, Venus the lover, Mars the warrior) simply does not exist as night-sky objects. The dominant actors in the ${obs} sky are the outer giants. Religion becomes <em>titan-based</em>: the great patient slow-moving planets are the primary deities, and the inner system appears only as a chorus of faint near-Sun heralds. A civilization here would develop a mythology of cold sovereignty, long oaths, and the patience of geologic time — not the hot drama of inner-system politics.`;

  const night=metrics.filter(m=>m.midFrac>0.5);
  if(night.length>0) return `<strong>The midnight dominants define everything.</strong> From ${obs}, the bodies that can appear at true midnight — deep in the night sky, hours from the horizon — are: ${night.map(m=>m.name).join(', ')}. These are the unchallenged authorities of ${obs}'s theology. A civilization here develops its primary religious architecture around these bodies because they are the ones that ancient observers could track reliably: visible for hours, rising and setting like the Sun, available for systematic measurement. The authority of the midnight wanderer — something that can be above the horizon for an entire night — becomes the template for divine sovereignty.`;

  return `<strong>Adjacency defines divinity.</strong> From ${obs}, the brightest night presence is ${top} — not because of any special intrinsic quality, but because it is the nearest massive moving object. Myth follows proximity and brightness. The theologies that emerge from any sky are not arbitrary: they are structured by the same mechanical question that determined survival for early astronomers — <em>what is closest, what is brightest, what can be tracked?</em> ${top} passes both tests from ${obs}. The civilization builds its calendar, its royalty, and its afterlife around this one fact.`;
}

